<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Tell your group to keep the mobs in the center of the room.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'll point out that the mob there is a wizard mob(he had been trying to root me).  The melees could move to the center of the room in an attempt to pull, however, the mob would most likely take his sweet time moving there, casting several nukes along the way.  Apart from my bolt, there is no other good reason to fight the mob in the center of the room.<br>
<br>
Besides, that mob doesn't really look close to the wall to me.  I am positive that I've hit mobs that were a lot closer to the wall.  <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Ask shamans to shrink everybody and to cast Grow on you so your bolts go over their head. Ask an enchanter to cast ogre on you and gnome on everyone else.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Great if you have someone that can shrink and the Enchanter aa illusion ability.  My point in the other thread was not(<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color: red;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">not!</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->) that bolts are useless.  My point was very far from that.  One of the main things I talked about was hidden costs..  for instance, if the melees were to try to move the mob away from the wall, I might have to wait 2 seconds before firing the bolt, consequently nullifying the usefulness of FoT's great DPS(relative to a nuke, anyway).  Requiring a shrinker?  Hmm do wizards need to bother everyone to get shrinks in order to use their spells?  Of course there is also the option to.. use normal nuke instead.<br>
<br>
But that was the other thread.  The point of this thread was to show how hard it is to tell whether your bolt will land sometimes.  I mean, that mob does not look against the wall to me, and he's even leaning backwards from casting a spell.. he wasn't when I started casting.  I <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">know</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> I've hit mobs closer to the wall than that before.  Furthermore, if someone IS supposed to recognize this as a &quot;no bolt&quot; situation, where is the in-game logic?  According to the game as a player is intended to see it, there is clearly nothing in between me and the mob.  It's only if I know about programming quirks that I can know enough to not use my bolt in this situation.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A> at: 12/20/02 10:13:12 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=milaru00>Milaru 00</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 1247<br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/20/02 10:16 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wow, using a bolt DOES take skill!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The sneakers that those skeletons are wearing were put on forcibly by my evil, possessed computer. (I'm pretty sure I have some corrupted files but I've been too lazy/buzy to patch them).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
